PART B — THE HOUSE INSTRUMENT LICENSE (reserved, commercial)
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The MIT grant in Part A covers the Software: the ballistic walk, the reef, the
144-anchor lattice, the placement/drift receipts, and the demos. Run them, fork
them, sell software built on them — freely.

What Part A does NOT grant, and what is EXPRESSLY RESERVED to ThetaDriven Inc.,
is the right to originate, price, underwrite, settle, clear, list, or sell any
FINANCIAL INSTRUMENT whose trigger, exclusion, premium, coverage, or settlement
references a ThetaCog placement or drift receipt — including without limitation:

  • insurance or reinsurance policies (AI-liability, scope-breach exclusions,
    affirmative AI cover, silent-AI riders);
  • surety, fidelity, or performance BONDS keyed to an agent staying in-lane;
  • OPTIONS, swaps, or other derivatives priced on the volatility of a placement
    coordinate (the σ, the in-lane put, the strike);
  • catastrophe or PARAMETRIC bonds triggered by an off-lane / rupture event;
  • any attestation-fee, oracle, or clearing service that monetizes the receipts
    as the settlement layer of such an instrument.

To build, operate, or monetize any instrument in the above class you need a
separate written commercial license from ThetaDriven Inc. — the "House
Instrument License" — which carries a per-attestation fee. This is the fourth
trust primitive (double-entry → blockchain → Black-Scholes → this): the decidable
semantic slice is open so anyone can verify it; the instruments priced on top of
it are the licensed asset.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
THE ATTESTATION UNIT AND THE STANDARD-OF-CARE BENCHMARK
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

The commercial unit is the AGENT-YEAR: USD $20, billed annually, per agent.

One agent-year covers up to 10,000 attestations. That ceiling is not arbitrary —
it is one REEF EPOCH: the 144 × 144 placement lattice holds 20,736 coordinates,
and responsible fill is capped at 70% (≈ 14,500 distinguishable placements) before
the grid saturates. 10,000 sits under that ceiling with headroom; when a reef
saturates, the epoch rolls to the next agent-year unit. Price therefore scales
with raw throughput — a busier agent consumes more agent-year units — at zero
marginal hosting cost, because the instrument runs air-gapped on the licensee's
own silicon.

At $20 per 10,000 attestations, deterministic attribution costs $0.002 — two-
tenths of a cent — per insurable decision: a signed, re-runnable record of WHERE
each decision landed, provable on the licensee's own hardware. (WHETHER a decision
was correct stays undecidable (Rice); this license makes no such claim. Only the
placement — the WHERE — is attested.) The standard is open-source (Part A),
deployable today, and priced at a rounding error on a single hour of the agent's
output. What a reasonable operator does with a safeguard that is cheap, available,
and working is a question the licensee's own counsel is equipped to answer.

Where an instrument (Part B) references these attestations, coverage may be
conditioned on the insured maintaining attestation on covered agents; a carrier
may also acquire agent-year units on an insured's behalf and bundle them into the
premium. Such arrangements are governed by the separate House Instrument License.

